A damning indictment on Parliament’s security. Cape Town firefighters have discovered sprinkler valves in the National Assembly building did not activate and were last serviced in 2017. Even more damning, is that several fire-safety breaches were highlighted previously during City inspections ahead of State of the Nation Addresses. eNCA's Lindsay Dentlinger reports. Courtesy #DStv403 CAPE TOWN - Parliament has been found lax in keeping its fire-safety systems in working order. A City of Cape Town fire incident report has revealed several issues of non-compliance. READ: Parliament fire | South Africans urged to wait for full report This appears to have led to the fire of the 2nd of January not being contained and raging through the historic buildings. Public Works has declared the National Assembly building unsafe and recommended it be cordoned off and closed immediately. READ: Parliament fire | Report exposes list of non-compliance issues Due to the destruction, the State of the Nation Address scheduled for 10 February will move to Cape Town’s City Hall. Public Works has started the process of enlisting an independent specialist engineering team to conduct further assessments and to test the structure of the building. * eNCA's Lindsay Dentlinger reports.